WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.600
6.0 English From BBCLearningEnglish.com

2
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.200
Hello, this is 6 minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Phil.

3
00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:13.200
And I'm Georgie.

4
00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:17.200
The exciting thing about technology is that it's always changing.

5
00:00:17.200 --> 00:00:23.200
Can you remember when computer floppy disks hand-held gameboys and fax machines were in fashion?

6
00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:27.600
Do you still have a Walkman cassette player from the 1980s?

7
00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:33.200
Today, technology progresses so quickly that old tech soon becomes obsolete.

8
00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:38.200
No longer in use, having been replaced by something better or more fashionable.

9
00:00:38.200 --> 00:00:47.800
So, you might be surprised to hear that until recently the government of Japan still used 3.5 inch floppy disks to store official documents.

10
00:00:47.800 --> 00:00:52.200
That around the world, music cassettes and walkmins are making a comeback.

11
00:00:52.600 --> 00:01:00.600
And even the world famous Swiss-sern physics laboratory uses old-fashioned magnetic tape reels to record its data.

12
00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:05.600
Yes, it seems that some old technology just refuses to die.

13
00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:12.600
Maybe because people still love it or maybe because of the old English proverb, if it ain't broke, don't fix it.

14
00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:15.800
Meaning that things should only be changed if they don't work.

15
00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:21.000
So, in this program, we'll be hearing about old tech which continues to be used today.

16
00:01:21.400 --> 00:01:25.200
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary as well.

17
00:01:25.200 --> 00:01:28.200
But first, I have a question for you, Georgie.

18
00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:32.400
Computers have seen some of the biggest advances in technology.

19
00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:38.800
But what was the name of the first computer developed for home use in the UK?

20
00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:46.400
Was it A, the Commodore 64, B, the Sinclair ZX80?

21
00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:49.400
Well, C, the BBC Micro?

22
00:01:50.200 --> 00:01:52.800
I guess it was the Commodore 64.

23
00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:57.600
Okay, Georgie, we'll find out if that's the correct answer later in the program.

24
00:01:57.600 --> 00:02:03.400
One reason for not updating tech is if the original design still works well.

25
00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:12.800
NASA engineer Jonathan Souter designed Harvey, a mechanical rover able to survive the inhospitable conditions on Venus,

26
00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:17.400
where temperatures reach 460 degrees Celsius.

27
00:02:17.400 --> 00:02:23.200
His Jonathan, talking to BBC World Service program, tech life.

28
00:02:23.200 --> 00:02:26.400
Venus has a very long night.

29
00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:31.000
It's actually about 60 days long that you're in total darkness.

30
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:43.800
So that's where we came up with a concept for Harvey, a mechanical clockwork rover that could be powered by Venus's winds in order to allow it to survive Venus's long hot night.

31
00:02:43.800 --> 00:02:48.200
Conditions on Venus mean that ordinary electronics simply won't work.

32
00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:56.000
That's why Jonathan built a clockwork rover, a machine with springs and wheels inside, which works when it's wound up with a key.

33
00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:01.600
Clockwork technology from the first century being used in 2024 by NASA.

34
00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:07.000
Other tech, which refuses to die, is just too much trouble to change.

35
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:12.000
For example, countries around the world use different electrical plugs,

36
00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:16.800
which would be better to standardise, but imagine the work involved.

37
00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:29.800
Here, Chris Fallen's presenter of BBC World Services TechLife discusses a similar example with Dr. Tacy Phillips and Science Curator at the National Museum of Scotland.

38
00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:38.000
Another piece of tech that people say has sort of refused to die is the Quarty keyboard, the layout of keyboards that we all have.

39
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:43.800
And it's perhaps not the most efficient layout in terms of the speed of typing.

40
00:03:43.800 --> 00:03:47.400
It's the layout we're all really, really used to though.

41
00:03:47.400 --> 00:03:56.600
And if you see court reporters, denographers, they have special keyboards and can type so fast to take down verbatim.

42
00:03:56.600 --> 00:04:00.800
But they also look very complicated and I don't actually want to learn to use one of those.

43
00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:03.600
So I'll stick with Quarty for the moment.

44
00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:06.000
Chris and Tacy discussed Quarty.

45
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:15.600
The traditional typewriter arrangement of keys on a computer keyboard, in which the top line begins with the letters Q, W, E, R, T and Y.

46
00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:19.800
In terms of being able to type quickly, Quarty isn't the best.

47
00:04:19.800 --> 00:04:24.600
In fact, court reporters type much faster with alternative keyboards.

48
00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:28.600
Court reporters need to type fast to record cases verbatim,

49
00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:32.400
using exactly the same words that were originally spoken.

50
00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:37.000
But because everyone is used to Quarty keyboard, the tech lives on.

51
00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:39.400
That's why Tacy says she'll stick with Quarty.

52
00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:42.600
She'll continue using it and not change to something else.

53
00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:46.800
And speaking of Quarty keyboards has reminded me of my question, Georgie.

54
00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:52.200
Yes, you asked me the name of the first home computer released in the UK.

55
00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:55.400
And I guess it was the Commodore 64.

56
00:04:55.400 --> 00:04:58.600
Which was the wrong answer I'm afraid.

57
00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:03.600
In fact, the UK's first home computer was the Sing clear ZX80,

58
00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:09.200
which was released in 1980 and used a whopping 4 kilobit memory.

59
00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:11.000
That's about half an email.

60
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:17.000
OK, it's time to recap the vocabulary we've learned in this program starting with obsolete.

61
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:22.200
Meaning no longer in use, having been replaced by something newer or better.

62
00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:25.800
The idiom, if it ain't or isn't broke, don't fix it,

63
00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:30.400
is used to say that if something is working, there's no reason to try to change it.

64
00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:36.400
Clockwork machinery uses metal springs and wheels, which move when they're wound up with a key.

65
00:05:36.400 --> 00:05:40.200
Quarty refers to the traditional typewriter arrangement of keys,

66
00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:45.400
in which the top line begins with the letters, Q, W, E, R, T and Y.

67
00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:51.000
If you say something verbatim, you use exactly the same words that were originally used.

68
00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.800
And finally, to stick with something, means to continue using or doing it.

69
00:05:55.800 --> 00:06:01.200
Once again, our six minutes are up, but remember to join us again next time for more trending topics

70
00:06:01.200 --> 00:06:02.600
and useful vocabulary.

71
00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:05.200
Here at six minute English, goodbye for now.

72
00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:06.200
Bye!
